result.title: CATIA specific UX guidelines (for Next Gen apps)
1 | Colors appear as defined by the Platform
3 | The right Font and Font icons are supported
4 | 3DExperience signature are well integrated and Compass is operational in Topbar
5 | Topbar icons are well integrated and well used to access Platform services/data (content, social, notifs, prefs, help, etc.)
6 | App is well triggerable from Compass with all elements (App icon, App name, short name, tooltip, etc.)
7 | Brand and App name are well displayed in frame headers (Topbar or window)
9 | Search result panel is well integrated and operational
10 | App is compatible with the Windowing and Tiling system (Page and Windows)
11 | A Home page introduces the App
12 | Mouse and touchpad standard gestures are supported to select, edit, navigate and display Contextual menu
13 |  Mouse cursor changes following the navigation or the selection type
14 | Drag and drop pattern is well supported when it is useful
15 | Prehighlight, highlight and cross-highlight are well supported in all UI and viewers
16 | Standard Multi-selection is supported with the right gestures and key-modifiers
17 | Trap or trace selections are supported to multi-select with primary (left-drag) or secondary (with key-modifier) mouse gesture
18 | Cut/Copy/Paste capabilities are available everywhere to duplicate objects and reapply parameters
19 | Double-click activates or switches to object context (app/workbench)
20 | All basic interactions are user-friendly, easily discoverable and usable (mouse, scrolling, DnD, manipulators, etc.)
21 | All UI and viewers support 3DExperience (and CATIA) mouse profile
22 |  App respects 3DExperience Platform WebUX or CID UI themes and controls
23 | All UI elements are well layouted/spaced/aligned
24 | UI instantaneously responds to user actions (dialog opens fast, scrolling is reactive, etc.)
25 | Navigation instantaneously responds to user gestures
26 | Manipulators in 2D/3D viewers instantaneously responds to user actions
27 | UI component state, size and position persist when necessary (increase muscle memory and UI customization)
28 | Truncated text are using ellipses to denote missing content
29 | Buttons respond to the standard states with the right feedbacks (disable, normal, hover, active/pressed, etc.)
30 | All UI controls have understandable tooltips
31 | All texts of UI components (label, tooltip, etc.) are concise, understandable and respect case and punctuation rules.
32 | Shortcuts must be supported, standardized when shared commands between apps, customizable and displayed in tooltips and Contextual menu
33 | There is a call to action toward the important element to interact with and access irrelevant content is blocked
34 | Interactions receive immediate feedback to inform user
35 | Wizard (step-by-step component) or Assistant (Check-list component) explain and guide user inside a command or other user workflow
36 | Undo/Redo work properly and respond to Ctrl+Z and Ctrl+Y
37 | Loading indicators displays that the system is listening and responding
38 | Preferences are different to Modes and are well integrated in the new CID dialog
39 | Frame, dialogs and windows are responsive when resizing, mainly on small viewport
40 | Any dialog or panel offers its own Find/Search/Filter field to filter its content if necessary (not use the topbar Search field)
41 | Transient commands with validation open the appropriate type of window
42 | Dialog footer respects OK/Cancel/Apply organization, primary and secondary actions respond to keyboard entries
43 | Dialog header displays icon and name of the command (mainly if it is a feature created in the tree)
44 | Dialogs must be smaller than screen size and complete dialog content  is not scrollable, because can contain scrollable area
45 | Dialogs follow layout guidelines (tabs, sections, expanders, etc) and offer progressive disclosure on rarely use options
46 | Dialogs are migrated to CID technology
47 | If supported, Selection panel display parameters and informations on any selection
48 | Panels and Action bar sections are compatible within the same layout system
49 | Action bar is well migrated to version 3
50 | Action bar commands/modes are well organized, semantically or by process, through sections, groups, secondaries, etc.
51 | Action bar offers a way to quickly find commands
52 | Action bar and sections do not contain too many similar icons and use a color code to group commands
53 | Action bar section does not abuse flyouts and does not hide important functionalities in it
54 | Standard section with Cut/copy/paste and other general commands is available (ex-fixed area)
55 | If the App is complex with many sections, Essentials section with duplication of the main commands of the App is available
56 | The Action bar View section is well organized (4 groups) and support the View options panels
57 | Action bar is easily customizable so that user organizes his commands
58 | Context bar provides quick access to most relevant actions (extract of main AB commands) on selection
59 | App offers a Breadcrumb or another level selector to easily navigate in the model from a selection
60 | App uses the new Selection bar
61 | App uses the new Intra-command toolbar to display modes/options of a command
62 | App uses the new View bar attached to viewer to display visu modes/options
63 | Contextual menu is well designed and contains the right items
64 | Every access to an object should provide similar Contextual menu entries
65 | Icons within the App are designed as guidelines/color pallet, understandable and readable
66 | The same icon is used for the same use, different icons are enough different for different uses
67 | Icons use same symbols for similar metaphors (trash, pen, cross, plus)
68 | All icons are those of the Platform and are declared in the formal repository
69 | Simple-click in 2D/3D viewer selects object at the expected granularity and cross-highlight with other views
70 | App integrates the new V-Nav component to manage views
71 | All manipulators in 3D/2D are well designed, consistent and easy to use
72 | Single arrow displays direction and can be switched on click
73 | A light and readable Ruler displays the value of the performed operation
74 | Manipulator/Ruler labels can be edited to specify a precise value
75 | 3D/2D manipulators are converged with the good design and with selection style
76 | 3D transformations can be done through Robot
77 | Robot is either following default visual or the new black and white lighter Robot
78 | Robot hides irrelevant manipulator (when not usable nor available)
79 | Previsualization is available as often as possible
80 | Previsualization and live result must be converged to the good design
81 | All list, graph and table label are editable by click-click (for rename), when necessary
82 | List, table and graph are scrollable, in particular with mouse wheel
83 | List, table and graph can be resized by an easy way as user wants
84 | Graph/Spec tree is zoomable with an easy-to-use, progressive and aesthetic resizing behavior
85 | Graph/Spec tree is both in a panel like other UI component and can be switch to a transparent mode
86 | Graph/tree nodes are well composed with an icon and a label
87 | Graph/tree style is adapted to the needs : expander and indentation for a simple use, plus and connectors for expert use
88 | List/tree with multi-columns are well designed and support reorder/sort when necessary
89 | Tables are filterable, sortable and customizable (resize, reorder, etc.) if necessary
90 | User can search in the Documentation, directly from the frame in context.
91 | User Assistance is well integrated with 4 basic levels of help
92  |  Long help is illustrated with animated gif when justified
93 | A Guided tour at first use is proposed. Can be launched on demand
94 | Tutorial videos are proposed for specific use cases
95 | Errors are explicit to the user and are possible to correct
96 | Bugs are not impacting the capabilities and the stability of the app
97 | The system prevents me from commiting errors
98 | Alert and warning messages are clear enough to guide user to take appropriate action
99 | If the app existed in V5, it has a similar organization by default (if different is not necessary) to allow easier transition from the user
100 | App automatically adapts to all devices (mainly small and big touch screens)
104 | App globally supports Hybrid touch/keyboard devices (like Surface Pro or Laptop with touch screen)
105 | App globally supports ultra-large touch screens (UHD/4K with touch capabilities)
106 | All UI components and viewers support standard navigation Touch gestures.
107 | Simple-tap selects or activate object similarly to left-click
108 | Double-tap opens or trigger Edition of complex object, similarly to double-click
109 | Long-tap displays Contextual menu when necessary or other secondary action, similarly to right-click
110 | List, tree and table are scrollable on touch drag
111 | Buttons are touch compatible, size, picking size, etc.
112 | Drag and drop is supported, as first manipulation or second (with long-tap)
113 | App provides if necessary capability to multi-select in Touch
114 | App responds correctly when the keyboard is displayed on screen
115 | App uses a new Phone-first UI, in particular the Mobile Action Bar (MAB)
